Core Commands

terraform init
Initializes a Terraform project. Downloads providers, modules, and configures the backend.
bashterraform init
Upgrade providers to the latest allowed version.
bashterraform init -upgrade
Migrate state when changing backend configuration.
bashterraform init -migrate-state
Pass backend config values directly — useful for CI/CD secrets.
bashterraform init \
  -backend-config="bucket=my-state-bucket" \
  -backend-config="key=prod/terraform.tfstate" \
  -backend-config="region=us-east-1"

terraform fmt
Formats Terraform files using Terraform standards. Improves readability and standardizes code.
bashterraform fmt
Format all directories recursively.
bashterraform fmt -recursive
CI mode — fails if any file needs formatting (does not modify files).
bashterraform fmt -check

terraform validate
Checks Terraform syntax. Verifies references, variables, and providers. Does NOT create infrastructure.
bashterraform validate

terraform plan
Shows the execution plan before making changes. Displays what Terraform will create, update, or destroy.
bashterraform plan
Pass variables from the command line.
bashterraform plan -var="aws_region=us-east-1"
Pass variables from a file.
bashterraform plan -var-file=production.tfvars
Save the plan to a file — always do this in CI/CD.
bashterraform plan -out=tfplan
Show plan in JSON format — useful for OPA policy evaluation.
bashterraform show -json tfplan | jq .
Target a specific resource.
bashterraform plan -target="aws_instance.web_server"
Mark a resource for forced replacement.
bashterraform plan -replace="aws_instance.web_server"
Disable state refresh — faster when no drift is expected.
bashterraform plan -refresh=false
Detect-only mode — exit code 2 means drift was found.
bashterraform plan -detailed-exitcode
Destroy plan — preview what would be deleted.
bashterraform plan -destroy

terraform apply
Creates or updates infrastructure.
bashterraform apply
Always apply from a saved plan in production.
bashterraform apply tfplan
Pass variables.
bashterraform apply -var="aws_region=us-east-1"
Automatic approval — for CI/CD only, never for manual production runs.
bashterraform apply -auto-approve
Reduce parallelism to avoid provider rate limits (default is 10).
bashterraform apply -parallelism=5
Structured JSON output — useful for logging and audit.
bashterraform apply -json tfplan 2>&1 | tee apply.log

terraform destroy
Deletes all infrastructure managed by Terraform.
bashterraform destroy
Target destruction of a specific resource.
bashterraform destroy -target="module.database"

terraform show
Displays the current Terraform state. Useful for inspecting deployed resources.
bashterraform show
Export state as JSON.
bashterraform show -json
Show a saved plan.
bashterraform show tfplan

terraform output
Displays output variables defined in the configuration.
bashterraform output
Show a specific output.
bashterraform output public_ip
Get all outputs as JSON — useful for scripting.
bashterraform output -json
Extract a specific value with jq.
bashterraform output -json | jq '.load_balancer_dns.value'
Example output definition:
hcloutput "public_ip" {
  description = "Public IP of the web server"
  value       = aws_instance.web.public_ip
}

terraform providers
Displays all providers required by the configuration.
bashterraform providers
Mirror providers to another location — useful for air-gapped environments.
bashterraform providers mirror /path/to/plugins
Lock provider versions for all target platforms — commit the lock file to Git.
bashterraform providers lock \
  -platform=linux_amd64 \
  -platform=darwin_arm64 \
  -platform=windows_amd64

terraform graph
Displays resource dependencies in DOT format.
bashterraform graph
Generate a visual SVG — requires Graphviz installed.
bashterraform graph | dot -Tsvg > graph.svg
Useful for troubleshooting and architecture visualization.

terraform console
Opens an interactive Terraform console. Useful for testing functions and expressions.
bashterraform console
Examples:
text> max(-1, 2, -10, 200)
200

> min(-1, 2, -10, 200)
-10

> upper("ibm")
"IBM"

> lower("IBM")
"ibm"

> length(["a", "b", "c"])
3

> toset(["apple", "apple", "banana"])
toset(["apple", "banana"])

> cidrsubnet("10.0.0.0/16", 8, 1)
"10.0.1.0/24"

> cidrhost("10.0.1.0/24", 5)
"10.0.1.5"

> format("%s-%s", "prod", "api")
"prod-api"

> contains(["dev", "prod"], "prod")
true

terraform workspace
Workspaces allow multiple environments using the same code.
Create a workspace.
bashterraform workspace new dev
List workspaces.
bashterraform workspace list
Select a workspace.
bashterraform workspace select dev
Display the current workspace.
bashterraform workspace show
Delete a workspace.
bashterraform workspace delete dev
Reference the current workspace in configuration.
hclterraform.workspace

⚠️ Workspaces share the same backend and provider credentials. For true production isolation — separate AWS accounts, different blast radius — use separate directories per environment instead of workspaces.


terraform state list
Lists all resources stored in the Terraform state file.
bashterraform state list

terraform state show
Displays detailed information about a specific resource.
bashterraform state show aws_instance.web

terraform state mv
Moves resources inside the Terraform state. Useful during refactoring.
bashterraform state mv aws_instance.web module.compute.aws_instance.web
Move a for_each resource.
bashterraform state mv 'aws_subnet.this["old-key"]' 'aws_subnet.this["new-key"]'

terraform state pull
Downloads the remote state file to stdout — useful for manual inspection or backup.
bashterraform state pull > backup.tfstate

terraform state rm
Removes a resource from the Terraform state. Does NOT delete the real infrastructure.
bashterraform state rm aws_instance.web

terraform import
Imports existing infrastructure into Terraform. Only updates the state file — Terraform does NOT generate HCL code automatically.
bashterraform import aws_instance.web i-0123456789
Import a for_each resource.
bashterraform import 'aws_subnet.this["private-1"]' subnet-0abc123
After importing, always run plan to verify alignment.
bashterraform plan  # Should show no changes if import was correct

💡 Terraform 1.5+ introduced import blocks in HCL, allowing imports to be declared as code and reviewed in PRs.

hclimport {
  to = aws_s3_bucket.my_bucket
  id = "my-existing-bucket-name"
}

terraform taint / -replace
Marks a resource for recreation during the next apply.
bashterraform taint aws_instance.web
Modern recommendation — prefer -replace over taint.
bashterraform apply -replace="aws_instance.web"

terraform untaint
Removes the tainted state from a resource.
bashterraform untaint aws_instance.web

terraform refresh
Synchronizes Terraform state with real infrastructure.
bashterraform refresh

⚠️ This command is mostly obsolete. Terraform automatically refreshes state during plan and apply. Use terraform plan instead.


terraform force-unlock
Force-releases a stuck state lock. Use carefully — only when a lock is genuinely stuck.
bashterraform force-unlock LOCK_ID

