Expressions & Functions
hcl# Conditional expression (ternary)
instance_type = var.environment == "prod" ? "m5.xlarge" : "t3.micro"

# String functions
upper("hello")              # => "HELLO"
lower("WORLD")              # => "world"
format("%s-%s", env, app)   # => "prod-api"
trimspace("  hello  ")      # => "hello"
replace("a-b-c", "-", "_")  # => "a_b_c"
split(",", "a,b,c")         # => ["a", "b", "c"]
join("-", ["a", "b"])        # => "a-b"

# Collection functions
length(["a", "b", "c"])           # => 3
contains(["a", "b"], "a")         # => true
flatten([["a"], ["b", "c"]])       # => ["a", "b", "c"]
merge({ a = 1 }, { b = 2 })       # => { a = 1, b = 2 }
keys({ a = 1, b = 2 })            # => ["a", "b"]
values({ a = 1, b = 2 })          # => [1, 2]
lookup(var.tags, "env", "unknown") # safe map lookup with default
coalesce(var.override, local.default)  # first non-null value
try(var.config.optional_field, "default")  # safe attribute access

# CIDR helpers
cidrsubnet("10.0.0.0/16", 8, 1)  # => "10.0.1.0/24"
cidrhost("10.0.1.0/24", 5)        # => "10.0.1.5"

# Filesystem functions
file("./scripts/init.sh")       # read file contents
filebase64("./certs/cert.pem")  # read as base64
templatefile("./tmpl.tpl", { region = var.region })  # render template

For Expressions
hcl# Transform a list
locals {
  upper_zones = [for az in var.availability_zones : upper(az)]
}

# Filter a list
locals {
  prod_instances = [for id, inst in var.instances : inst if inst.env == "prod"]
}

# Transform list to map
locals {
  instance_ids = { for name, inst in aws_instance.servers : name => inst.id }
}

# Splat expression — shorthand for list of attribute values
all_ids = aws_subnet.private[*].id

Dynamic Blocks
hclvariable "ingress_rules" {
  type = list(object({
    port        = number
    protocol    = string
    description = string
    cidr_blocks = list(string)
  }))
  default = [
    { port = 443, protocol = "tcp", description = "HTTPS", cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"] },
    { port = 80,  protocol = "tcp", description = "HTTP",  cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"] },
  ]
}

resource "aws_security_group" "web" {
  name   = "web-sg"
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  dynamic "ingress" {
    for_each = var.ingress_rules

    content {
      from_port   = ingress.value.port
      to_port     = ingress.value.port
      protocol    = ingress.value.protocol
      description = ingress.value.description
      cidr_blocks = ingress.value.cidr_blocks
    }
  }

  egress {
    from_port   = 0
    to_port     = 0
    protocol    = "-1"
    cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
    description = "Allow all outbound"
  }
}

Modules
Modules are containers for multiple resources used together. They enable code reuse, enforce standards, and let teams compose infrastructure from well-tested building blocks.
Standard Module Structure
textmodules/networking/vpc/
├── main.tf          # Core resources
├── variables.tf     # Input variables
├── outputs.tf       # Exported values
├── versions.tf      # Provider & Terraform version constraints
├── README.md        # Auto-generated via terraform-docs
└── examples/
    └── basic/
        ├── main.tf
        └── outputs.tf
Writing a Module
hcl# modules/networking/vpc/main.tf
resource "aws_vpc" "this" {
  cidr_block           = var.cidr_block
  enable_dns_hostnames = true
  enable_dns_support   = true

  tags = merge(var.tags, { Name = var.name })
}

resource "aws_subnet" "private" {
  count = length(var.private_subnet_cidrs)

  vpc_id            = aws_vpc.this.id
  cidr_block        = var.private_subnet_cidrs[count.index]
  availability_zone = var.availability_zones[count.index]

  tags = merge(var.tags, {
    Name = "${var.name}-private-${count.index + 1}"
    Tier = "private"
  })
}
Calling a Module
hclmodule "vpc" {
  source  = "../../modules/networking/vpc"
  # Or from Terraform Registry:
  # source  = "terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws"
  # version = "~> 5.0"

  name       = local.name_prefix
  cidr_block = var.vpc_cidr

  availability_zones   = data.aws_availability_zones.available.names
  private_subnet_cidrs = local.private_subnet_cidrs
  public_subnet_cidrs  = local.public_subnet_cidrs

  tags = local.common_tags
}

# Access module outputs
resource "aws_instance" "app" {
  subnet_id = module.vpc.private_subnet_ids[0]
}
Module Sources
Source TypeExampleLocal path"../../modules/networking"Terraform Registry"terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws"GitHub (tagged)"github.com/org/repo//path?ref=v1.2.3"S3 bucket"s3::https://s3.amazonaws.com/bucket/module.zip"

💡 Always version-pin external modules. Use the Terraform Registry for well-maintained modules — terraform-aws-modules is the gold standard for AWS.


State Management & Remote Backends
Why Remote State?
Local state is only suitable for personal experiments. Remote state enables team collaboration, state locking to prevent concurrent modifications, and versioning for rollback. All production Terraform must use a remote backend.
AWS S3 Backend (Most Common)
hcl# backend.tf
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket         = "mycompany-terraform-state"
    key            = "environments/production/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "us-east-1"
    encrypt        = true
    kms_key_id     = "arn:aws:kms:us-east-1:123456789012:key/mrk-xxx"

    # State locking via DynamoDB
    dynamodb_table = "terraform-state-locks"
  }
}
Bootstrap the State Infrastructure
hclresource "aws_s3_bucket" "terraform_state" {
  bucket = "mycompany-terraform-state"

  lifecycle {
    prevent_destroy = true
  }
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket_versioning" "terraform_state" {
  bucket = aws_s3_bucket.terraform_state.id
  versioning_configuration { status = "Enabled" }
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket_server_side_encryption_configuration" "terraform_state" {
  bucket = aws_s3_bucket.terraform_state.id
  rule {
    apply_server_side_encryption_by_default {
      sse_algorithm     = "aws:kms"
      kms_master_key_id = aws_kms_key.terraform_state.arn
    }
  }
}

resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "terraform_state_lock" {
  name         = "terraform-state-locks"
  billing_mode = "PAY_PER_REQUEST"
  hash_key     = "LockID"

  attribute {
    name = "LockID"
    type = "S"
  }
}
State Commands — SRE Daily Operations
bash# List all resources in state
terraform state list

# Inspect a specific resource
terraform state show "aws_instance.web_server"

# Rename resource after refactoring
terraform state mv "aws_instance.old_name" "aws_instance.new_name"

# Move resource into a module
terraform state mv "aws_instance.web" "module.compute.aws_instance.web"

# Unmanage a resource without destroying it
terraform state rm "aws_instance.legacy"

# Import existing resource
terraform import aws_s3_bucket.my_bucket my-existing-bucket-name

# Force-unlock a stuck state (use carefully!)
terraform force-unlock LOCK_ID

# Backup current remote state locally
terraform state pull > backup.tfstate

