Common Interview Questions
Q: What is Terraform state and why is it important?
State is a JSON mapping between your Terraform configuration and real-world infrastructure. It stores resource IDs, metadata, and dependencies. Without state, Terraform cannot make safe incremental changes — it wouldn't know what already exists. State enables the execution plan by comparing current state to desired configuration. State locking prevents two engineers from running apply simultaneously and corrupting infrastructure.
Q: How do you handle Terraform in a team of 20 engineers?
Remote state backend with locking (S3 + DynamoDB for AWS). CI/CD pipeline where plans run on PRs and applies happen after approval on main. A versioned module library so teams share tested building blocks. Mandatory code review for all infrastructure changes. Automated security scanning (tfsec, checkov) and scheduled drift detection.
Q: A colleague manually deleted a resource Terraform manages. What do you do?
Run terraform plan — it will show the resource as needing to be created. If we want to recreate it, terraform apply provisions it fresh. If a replacement was manually created, use terraform import to bring it under Terraform management. Going forward: IAM policies restricting console modifications, drift detection alerts, and a post-mortem to strengthen runbooks.
Q: Explain the difference between count and for_each.
count creates a list-indexed set of resources (aws_subnet.private[0], [1], [2]). If you remove a middle element, Terraform renumbers all subsequent resources — causing unwanted replacements. for_each creates a map-keyed set (aws_subnet.private["private-1"]). Removing an element only deletes that specific resource. Use count only for simple boolean existence (count = var.enabled ? 1 : 0). Use for_each for everything else.
Anti-Patterns to Know

Hardcoded values everywhere — use variables and locals.
Manual state edits — always use terraform state commands.
No remote state in teams — local tfstate is a collaboration disaster.
No version pinning — unpinned providers cause surprise breakages.
Giant monolithic modules — modules should do one thing well.
Secrets in tfvars or code — use Secrets Manager, Vault, or SOPS.
No -out flag in CI/CD — always save plans to avoid drift between plan and apply.
Overuse of -target — leaves state inconsistent and creates technical debt.
No drift detection — manual changes silently diverge from code.
No tagging strategy — impossible to attribute costs without consistent tags.


